Indexing¶

In [12]:
# index is like primary key in database (unique number assigned to each observation)
df.index
Out[12]:
RangeIndex(start=0, stop=99404, step=1)

By default, index starts from 0.

This data contains date column so we can do time series analysis. Exciting! For this, set date column as the index column.

In [13]:
# then set datetime [date] column as index (primary key). without this data transformation, you will receive error messages later.

df=df.set_index('flightdate')
df.head(2)

Customizing plots with .plot() parameters You can customize plots a number of ways. Heres a quick guide to common parameters: kind=: line, bar, barh, hist, box, area, scatter figsize=: (width, height) in inches colormap=: a long list of color palettes, including: autumn, winter, summer title=: a string stacked=: stack the values vertically (instead of allowing them to overlap) source: https://community.modeanalytics.com/python/tutorial/pandas-groupby-and-python-lambda-functions/
